## 5. Custom Lexical Plugin Approach

### `ParagraphCommentPlugin` -- Full Design with Code Snippets

This is the most technically nuanced part. The plugin needs to:
1. Detect all paragraph/heading DOM elements within the read-only editor
2. Overlay comment count badges on the right margin
3. Handle click events to open the comment thread
4. Update badges when comment counts change

```jsx
// ParagraphCommentPlugin.jsx
import { useEffect, useRef, useCallback } from 'react';
import { useLexicalComposerContext } from '@lexical/react/LexicalComposerContext';

/**
 * Props:
 *   commentCounts: Record<string, number>  -- { paragraphId: count }
 *   paragraphIdMap: Record<string, string>  -- maps DOM data-paragraph-id -> paragraphId
 *   onParagraphClick: (paragraphId: string) => void
 *   contentJson: object  -- the parsed Lexical JSON (to extract paragraphIds)
 */
export default function ParagraphCommentPlugin({
    commentCounts,
    onParagraphClick,
    contentJson,
}) {
    const [editor] = useLexicalComposerContext();
    const badgeContainerRef = useRef(null);
    const badgesRef = useRef(new Map()); // paragraphId -> badge DOM element

    // Build a map of paragraph index -> paragraphId from the JSON
    const paragraphIds = useRef([]);

    useEffect(() => {
        if (!contentJson?.root?.children) return;
        const ids = [];
        for (const child of contentJson.root.children) {
            if (child.type === 'paragraph' || child.type === 'heading') {
                ids.push(child.paragraphId || null);
            }
        }
        paragraphIds.current = ids;
    }, [contentJson]);

    // Create and position badge elements after the editor renders
    const updateBadges = useCallback(() => {
        const rootElement = editor.getRootElement();
        if (!rootElement) return;

        // Find all top-level paragraph/heading elements
        const paragraphElements = rootElement.querySelectorAll(
            '.editor-paragraph, .editor-heading-h1, .editor-heading-h2, .editor-heading-h3, .editor-quote'
        );

        // Clean up old badges
        badgesRef.current.forEach((badge) => badge.remove());
        badgesRef.current.clear();

        paragraphElements.forEach((el, index) => {
            const paragraphId = paragraphIds.current[index];
            if (!paragraphId) return;

            // Store the paragraphId as a data attribute for click handling
            el.dataset.paragraphId = paragraphId;
            el.style.position = 'relative';
            el.style.cursor = 'pointer';

            const count = commentCounts?.[paragraphId] || 0;

            // Create the badge element
            const badge = document.createElement('button');
            badge.className = count > 0
                ? 'pc-badge pc-badge--has-comments'
                : 'pc-badge pc-badge--empty';
            badge.setAttribute('aria-label', `${count} comments on this paragraph`);

            if (count > 0) {
                badge.innerHTML = `
                    <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor">
                        <path d="M21 15a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H7l-4 4V5a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h14a2 2 0 0 1 2 2z"/>
                    </svg>
                    <span class="pc-badge-count">${count}</span>
                `;
            } else {
                badge.innerHTML = `
                    <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none"
                         stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
                        <path d="M21 15a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H7l-4 4V5a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h14a2 2 0 0 1 2 2z"/>
                    </svg>
                `;
            }

            badge.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
                e.stopPropagation();
                onParagraphClick(paragraphId);
            });

            el.appendChild(badge);
            badgesRef.current.set(paragraphId, badge);
        });
    }, [editor, commentCounts, onParagraphClick]);

    // Also handle clicks on the paragraph text itself
    useEffect(() => {
        const rootElement = editor.getRootElement();
        if (!rootElement) return;

        const handleClick = (e) => {
            const target = e.target.closest('[data-paragraph-id]');
            if (target?.dataset?.paragraphId) {
                onParagraphClick(target.dataset.paragraphId);
            }
        };

        rootElement.addEventListener('click', handleClick);
        return () => rootElement.removeEventListener('click', handleClick);
    }, [editor, onParagraphClick]);

    // Run badge updates after editor renders and when counts change
    useEffect(() => {
        // Wait a frame for Lexical to finish rendering
        const frame = requestAnimationFrame(() => {
            updateBadges();
        });
        return () => cancelAnimationFrame(frame);
    }, [updateBadges, commentCounts]);

    // Also listen for DOM mutations (editor state changes)
    useEffect(() => {
        return editor.registerMutationListener(
            // Listen to any node type for DOM changes
            // ParagraphNode is from lexical core
            // We need to import it
            // For simplicity, just re-run on any update
        );
    }, [editor]);

    // Simpler approach: use editor.registerUpdateListener
    useEffect(() => {
        return editor.registerUpdateListener(() => {
            // Re-position badges after any editor state update
            requestAnimationFrame(updateBadges);
        });
    }, [editor, updateBadges]);

    return null; // Plugin renders nothing itself
}
```

**Important consideration about the DOM approach:** Since the `<LexicalComposer>` is `editable: false`, Lexical renders the content and then the DOM is static. We do not need to worry about frequent re-renders. The badges are created once when the component mounts, and updated only when `commentCounts` changes.

**Alternative approach using a wrapper div instead of DOM manipulation:**

Instead of appending badges directly to Lexical's DOM (which is somewhat fragile), a cleaner approach uses a **sibling overlay container** positioned absolutely alongside the editor content:

```jsx
// In ContentView.jsx
<div className="cv-body cv-body--with-comments" style={{ position: 'relative' }}>
    <LexicalComposer initialConfig={...}>
        <RichTextPlugin ... />
        <ParagraphCommentPlugin
            contentJson={parsedContent}
            onParagraphPositions={setParagraphPositions}
        />
    </LexicalComposer>

    {/* Badge overlay -- positioned absolutely on the right */}
    <div className="pc-badge-overlay">
        {paragraphPositions.map(({ paragraphId, top, height }) => (
            <button
                key={paragraphId}
                className={`pc-badge ${commentCounts[paragraphId] > 0 ? 'pc-badge--active' : ''}`}
                style={{ top: top, height: height }}
                onClick={() => setActiveParagraphId(paragraphId)}
            >
                {commentCounts[paragraphId] > 0 && (
                    <span className="pc-badge-count">
                        {commentCounts[paragraphId]}
                    </span>
                )}
            </button>
        ))}
    </div>
</div>
```

This overlay approach has the plugin measure paragraph positions and report them via callback, while the badges are rendered as React components in a sibling container. This is **cleaner** because:
- No direct DOM manipulation of Lexical's internal elements
- Badges are proper React components (can use Framer Motion, proper event handling)
- Easier to style responsively

**The `ParagraphCommentPlugin` in this approach would be simpler:**

```jsx
export default function ParagraphCommentPlugin({ contentJson, onParagraphPositions }) {
    const [editor] = useLexicalComposerContext();

    useEffect(() => {
        const rootElement = editor.getRootElement();
        if (!rootElement || !contentJson?.root?.children) return;

        const measure = () => {
            const paragraphElements = rootElement.querySelectorAll(
                '.editor-paragraph, .editor-heading-h1, .editor-heading-h2, .editor-heading-h3, .editor-quote'
            );

            const ids = [];
            const rootRect = rootElement.getBoundingClientRect();

            let idx = 0;
            for (const child of contentJson.root.children) {
                if (child.type === 'paragraph' || child.type === 'heading' || child.type === 'quote') {
                    const el = paragraphElements[idx];
                    if (el && child.paragraphId) {
                        const rect = el.getBoundingClientRect();
                        ids.push({
                            paragraphId: child.paragraphId,
                            top: rect.top - rootRect.top,
                            height: rect.height,
                        });
                    }
                    idx++;
                }
            }

            onParagraphPositions(ids);
        };

        // Measure after render
        requestAnimationFrame(measure);

        // Re-measure on window resize
        window.addEventListener('resize', measure);
        return () => window.removeEventListener('resize', measure);
    }, [editor, contentJson, onParagraphPositions]);

    return null;
}
```

**I recommend the overlay approach** for cleanliness.

